  { question: "Does Maine require vertical integration for cannabis businesses?", answer: "No. Maine does not require vertical integration. Operators may choose to hold a single license or multiple licenses based on their business strategy. This permissive framework distinguishes Maine from states that mandate or prohibit vertical integration, giving operators the flexibility to design their business model around market opportunity." },
  { question: "How much does it cost to start a vertically integrated cannabis business in Maine?", answer: "A fully vertically integrated operation in Maine typically requires $1.5 million to $5 million or more in total startup costs, including licensing, facility build-out, equipment, security, and working capital. A phased approach — starting with cultivation and retail, then adding manufacturing — can reduce initial capital requirements by 30–40%." },
  { question: "How long does it take to get all three licenses in Maine?", answer: "The full process from initial planning to operational launch typically takes 12–18 months. OCP application review takes 60–120 days per license, facility build-out takes 3–12 months depending on scope, and the first cultivation harvest adds 4–6 months after planting. Applying for all license types simultaneously can accelerate the overall timeline." },
  { question: "Can I operate cultivation and retail in different Maine towns?", answer: "Yes. Maine law does not require all licenses held by a single entity to be located within the same municipality. Many vertically integrated operators use a multi-town strategy, placing cultivation in agriculturally zoned areas, manufacturing in industrial zones, and retail in high-traffic commercial districts. Each location must comply with the ordinances of its respective municipality." },
  { question: "What is the Maine cannabis tax rate for vertically integrated operators?", answer: "Maine imposes a 14% excise tax on adult-use cannabis sales at the retail level (effective January 1, 2026), regardless of the operator's license structure. Vertically integrated operators also benefit from Maine's decoupling from federal IRC Section 280E, allowing them to deduct ordinary business expenses on state tax returns. For detailed 280E tax strategy, see our Maine Cannabis Taxation Guide." },
